re doing redundant work if Entire isn't set up.\\n\\nThe cleanest approach would be to check `settings.IsSetUpAndEnabled()` in the `PersistentPreRunE` of the git hooks command, and if it returns false, set a flag that makes all the subcommands return early.\\n\\nActually, even simpler: we can check in `PersistentPreRunE` and if Entire is not set up/enabled, just skip initializing logging and set a package-level flag. Then each hook command can check that flag and return early.\\n\\nOr we could add the check to `newGitHookContext()` and have it return nil if not enabled, then each command checks for nil.\\n\\nLet me think about the cleanest approach...\\n\\nActually, the simplest approach is to add a check at the start of each hook's `RunE` function. But that's repetitive.\\n\\nA better approach: add the check to `PersistentPreRunE` and store the result in a variable that the commands can check. Or better yet, make `PersistentPreRunE` set a \\\"skip hooks\\\" flag when not enabled, and have each command check that flag.\\n\\nActually the cleanest might be to add the check to `newGitHookContext` and have it set `g.strategy = nil` or something when not enabled, then the type assertion `if handler, ok := g.strategy.(...)` will just fail and the hook will be a no-op.\\n\\nLet me look at `newGitHookContext`:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc newGitHookContext(hookName string) *gitHookContext {\\n\\tg := &gitHookContext{\\n\\t\\thookName:     hookName,\\n\\t\\tstart:        time.Now(),\\n\\t\\tctx:          logging.WithComponent(context.Background(), \\\"hooks\\\"),\\n\\t\\tstrategyName: unknownStrategyName,\\n\\t}\\n\\tg.strategy = GetStrategy()\\n\\tg.strategyName = g.strategy.Name()\\n\\treturn g\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIf I make `GetStrategy()` return nil when not enabled, then `g.strategy.Name()` would panic. A cleaner approach: add a field to `gitHookContext` like `skip bool`, set it in `newGitHookContext()` when not enabled, and check it in each command.\\n\\nThe simplest solution is to che